'''Bradycardia''' is a condition wherein an individual has a slow [[heart_rate|heart rate]], typically defined as a [[heart_rate|heart rate]] of under 60 [[Heart_rate|beats per minute]] (BPM) in adults.<ref>{{cite web|title=Types of Arrhythmia|url=http://www.nhlbi.nih.gov/health/health-topics/topics/arr/types|accessdate=19 March 2015|date=July 1, 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150607165144/http://www.nhlbi.nih.gov/health/health-topics/topics/arr/types|archive-date=2015-06-07|dead-url=yes}}</ref> Bradycardia typically does not cause symptoms until the rate drops below 50 BPM. When symptomatic, it may cause fatigue, weakness, dizziness, sweating, and at very low rates, [[Syncope_(medicine)|fainting]].<ref name=SINUS-BRADYCARDIA>[http://www.emedicine.com/emerg/topic534.htm Sinus Bradycardia] {{Wayback|url=http://www.emedicine.com/emerg/topic534.htm |date=20081025115818 }} – eMedicine</ref>

During sleep, a slow heartbeat with rates around 40–50 BPM is common, and is considered normal.  Highly trained [[sportsperson|athlete]]s  may also have [[athletic_heart_syndrome|athletic heart syndrome]], a very slow resting heart rate that occurs as a sport adaptation and helps prevent [[tachycardia|tachycardia]] during training.

The term relative bradycardia is used in explaining a heart rate that, although not actually below 60 BPM, is still considered too slow for the individual's current medical condition.
